1. Main Formulas & Equations Used
Speed & Geometry

Synchronous Speed ($N_s$): (60 × Frequency) / Pole Pairs
Rated Speed ($N_r$): Sync Speed × 0.96 (Assumes a 4% slip/speed drop at rated load)
Pole Pitch ($\tau$): π × Rotor Radius / Pole Pairs
Mean Turn Length ($L_{mean}$): π × (Rotor Radius + Air Gap + 0.01) + 2 × Stack Length + 0.04
Slot Area: π × ((Stator OD - Rotor OD - 2 × Air Gap) / 4)² × ((Rotor Radius + Air Gap/2) × 2π / Slots) × 0.65
Magnetic & Electrical Constants

Peak Flux Density ($B_{peak}$): Rated Voltage / (4.44 × Freq × Turns × Pole Pairs × Pole Pitch × Stack Length) (Capped at a maximum saturation of 1.70 T)
Air Gap Flux Density ($B_{air}$): B_peak × 0.85
Skew Factor ($k_{skew}$): cos(Skew Angle / 2) (Angle in radians)
Wire Cross-Section Area ($A_w$): π × (Wire Diameter / 2)²
Phase Resistance ($R_{phase}$): (1.72e-8 × Turns × L_mean) / A_w (Using Copper's resistivity $\rho$)
Torque Constant ($K_t$) & Back-EMF Constant ($K_e$): (3 × Pole Pairs × B_air × Rotor Radius × Stack Length × Turns × 0.95) / π × k_skew
Performance & Outputs

Back-EMF: K_e × Operating Speed (in rad/s)
Torque ($\tau_{op}$): K_t × Applied Current (Varies slightly based on Const. CFM/Speed/Torque modes)
Shaft Power ($P_{shaft}$): Torque × Operating Speed (in rad/s)
Input Power ($P_{in}$): Applied Voltage × Applied Current × Power Factor
Copper Loss ($P_{cu}$): 3 × Applied Current² × (R_phase / 3)
Iron/Core Loss ($P_{fe}$): 0.003 × B_air² × Freq × (Stator OD)² × Stack Length × 7650 × 50 (Empirical volume-based estimate)
Efficiency ($\eta$): (Shaft Power / Input Power) × 100
Slot Fill Factor: (Turns × A_w) / Slot Area
Temperature Rise: Copper Loss / (10 × (π × Stator OD × Stack Length + 0.01)) (Simplified thermal dissipation based on outer surface area)
Fan CFM: 800 × (Operating Speed / Rated Speed)³ (Based on standard fan affinity laws)
2. Parameter Cause-and-Effect Matrix
This table shows exactly how changing an input slider shifts the simulation's results.

Note: This strictly follows the mathematical relationships hardcoded into this simulation engine. In reality, some parameters (like air gap) heavily impact flux density, but in this specific simplified script, flux density is primarily driven by voltage, frequency, and turns.

Parameter Increased	Primary Effects in this Simulation	Effect Magnitude
Stator Outer Dia	Increases Iron Loss (scales with OD²).Increases Slot Area (lowers fill factor risk).Decreases Temp Rise (more surface area to cool).	High
Stack Length	Increases Torque / $K_t$ (longer magnetic interaction).Increases Phase Resistance & Cu Loss (longer wires).Decreases Temp Rise (adds cooling surface area).	High
Slots	Decreases Slot Area.Increases Copper Volume/Mass.	Medium
Pole Pairs	Decreases Synchronous/Rated Speed.Increases Torque Constant ($K_t$).	High
Rotor Dia	Increases Torque / $K_t$ (larger lever arm).Decreases Slot Area (leaves less room for stator windings, skyrocketing Fill Factor).Increases Phase Resistance (wider loops).	High
Air Gap	Decreases Slot Area (pushes stator further out).Increases Phase Resistance slightly (longer wire spans).	Small
Skew Angle	Decreases Torque / $K_t$ (due to geometric misalignment, $\cos(\theta/2)$).	Medium
Turns / Slot	Increases Torque Constant ($K_t$).Increases Phase Resistance (longer wire).Increases Slot Fill Factor.Decreases Magnetic Flux Density ($B_{peak}$).	High
Wire Diameter	Decreases Phase Resistance (thicker wire = lower R).Decreases Copper Loss.Increases Slot Fill Factor (takes up more room).	High
Applied Voltage	Increases Operating Speed (shifts the V/Hz ratio up).Increases Input Power.Increases Copper & Iron losses marginally if speed rises.	High
Applied Current	Increases Output Torque linearly.Increases Copper Loss exponentially ($I^2R$).Increases Temp Rise.	High
